No Show Appointment Data Exploration¶

by Oluwatosin Durodola¶

Introduction¶

This dataset consist of over 110,000 medical appointments collected in Brazil and is focused on the question of whether or not patients show up for their appointment. A number of characteristics about the patient are included in each row.

Supporting Material: No Show Appointment

Data Source: Kaggle

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This document explores a dataset containing no show and attributes for approximately 110,527 medical appointments.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 110,527 patients in the dataset with 17 features (the actual 14 features and additional 3 features created by me) which are patientid, appointmentid, gender, schedule_date, appointment_date, age, neighbourhood, scholarship, hypertension, diabetes, alcoholism, handicap, sms_received, no_show, appointment_day, waiting_days and age_group. Some variables are objects, numeric in nature, but the variables gender, scholarship, hypertension, diabetes, alcoholism, handicap, and no_show are nominal factor variables with the following levels.

  • gender: F, M
  • scholarship: 0, 1
  • hypertension: 0, 1
  • diabetes: 0, 1
  • alcoholism: 0, 1
  • handicap: 0, 1
  • no_show: 0, 1

Moreove, there are two oridnal category variable which are appointment_day and age_group with the following values.

  • appointment_day: Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday and Saturday (working days for hospitals)
  • age_group: Early Childhood, Middle Childhood, Adolescence, Youthhood, Middle Age, Old Age

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting the reason why patients will book an appointment and yet still not show up for the appointment in the dataset.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that waiting_days will have the strongest effect on each patient's no_show. I also think other factors like age, scholarship, hypertension, diabetes, alcholism, handicap, sms_received, appointment_day and age_group will have effects on patients reponses to no_show though to a much smaller degree than the main effect of waiting_days.

Univariate Exploration¶

I will start by looking that the distribution of the variable of interest: no_show.

Therefore, I will write a function to plot a barchart to help me reduce repetition of codes.

In [14]:
def barchart_percent(var, figsize=[6.4, 4.8], yaxis=False, ordered=False):
    '''seaborn bar chart
    var - the column to plot,
    figsize - optional but can be provided
    yaxis=False - it means to plot on yaxis but if True
    it will be plotted on yaxis
    order=False | bool value - it means to plot according
    to the highest value
    '''
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]

    # Count the frequency of unique values  and return the sum of all value in the var column of no_show_app dataframe.
    var_counts = no_show_app[var].value_counts()
    var_order = no_show_app[var].value_counts().index
    n_var = no_show_app[var].value_counts().sum()

    # Return the highest frequency in the var column
    max_var_count = var_counts[0]

    # Return the maximum proportion, or in other words, 
    # compute the length of the longest bar in terms of the proportion
    max_prop = max_var_count/n_var
    
    if not yaxis:
        if not ordered:
            sb.countplot(data=no_show_app, x=var, color=base_color)
            # get the current tick locations and labels
            locs, labels = plt.xticks()

            # loop through each pair of locations and labels
            for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):

                # get the text property for the label to get the correct count
                count = var_counts[label.get_text()]
                pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_var)

                # print the annotation just below the top of the bar
                plt.text(loc, count+2, pct_string, ha='center', color='black')
            plt.show();
        else:
            sb.countplot(data=no_show_app, x=var, color=base_color, order=var_order)
            # get the current tick locations and labels
            locs, labels = plt.xticks()

            # loop through each pair of locations and labels
            for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):

                # get the text property for the label to get the correct count
                count = var_counts[label.get_text()]
                pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_var)

                # print the annotation just below the top of the bar
                plt.text(loc, count+2, pct_string, ha='center', color='black')
            plt.show();
    else:
        if not ordered:
            sb.countplot(data=no_show_app, y=var, color=base_color)
            
            # get the current tick locations and labels
            locs, labels = plt.yticks()
            
            for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):

                # get the text property for the label to get the correct count
                count = var_counts[label.get_text()]
                pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_var)

                # print the annotation just below the top of the bar
                plt.text(count+2, loc, pct_string, va='center', color='black')
            plt.show();
        else:
            sb.countplot(data=no_show_app, y=var, color=base_color, order=var_order)
            for i in range(var_counts.shape[0]):
                # Remember, type_counts contains the frequency of unique values in the var column in decreasing order.
                count = var_counts[i]
                # Convert count into a percentage, and then into string
                pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_var)
                plt.text(count+1, i, pct_string, va='center')
            plt.show();

def barplot(cat_v, nrows=1, figsize = [10,12]):
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(ncols = 2, nrows = nrows , figsize = figsize)

    for i in range(len(cat_v)):
        var = cat_v[i]
        sb.barplot(data = no_show_app, x = var, y = 'age', ax = ax[i,0],
                   color = base_color)
        sb.barplot(data = no_show_app, x = var, y = 'waiting_days', ax = ax[i,1],
                   color = base_color)

    plt.show();

Conclusions¶

In conclusion, the waiting days of patients between date of schedule and date of appointment seems to be the major factor that contribute to the no show of patients; having the about 15 average waiting days compare to patients that shows up with an avearage waiting days of 15.

And also, the appointment day which is Saturday has lower patients rate and yet still have the higtest rate of not showing up for their appointment.
